Group sales = new SimpleGroup("sales");
identityManager.add(sales);
User janet = identityManager.getUser("janet");
identityManager.addToGroup(janet, sales);

Group sales = identityManager.getGroup("sales");
User janet = identityManager.getUser("janet");
identityManager.removeFromGroup(janet, sales);

Group sales = identityManager.getGroup("sales");
User janet = identityManager.getUser("janet");
boolean isJanetInSales = identityManager.isMember(janet, sales);

section.section:
        Group Role



          The GroupRole relationship type extends GroupMembership by adding a role property, and is
          used to represent identities that have a specific role within the context of a group. 














            While the GroupRole relationship type extends GroupMembership, it does not 
            mean that a member of a GroupRole automatically receives GroupMembership membership also.





          The GroupRole relationship type should be used when it is intended for an identity to perform a specific
          role for a group, but not be an actual member of the group itself.  For example, an administrator of a group of doctors
          may not be a doctor themselves, but have an administrative role to perform for them.  If the intent is for an individual
          identity to both be a member of a group and have an assigned role in that group also, then the identity
          should have both GroupRole and GroupMembership relationships for that group.




          The IdentityManager interface provides some convenience methods for managing group roles.  The following example
          demonstrates how to assign a group role to a user:


          Group doctors = new SimpleGroup("doctors");
identityManager.add(doctors);
User sally = identityManager.getUser("sally");
Role admin = identityManager.getRole("administrator");
identityManager.grantGroupRole(sally, doctors, admin);



          The above code is equivalent to creating a GroupRole relationship manually, and adding it via the 
          add() method:


          Group doctors = new SimpleGroup("doctors");
identityManager.add(doctors);
User sally = identityManager.getUser("sally");
Role admin = identityManager.getRole("administrator");
GroupRole groupRole = new GroupRole(sally, doctors, admin);
identityManager.add(groupRole);\



          A group role can be revoked using the revokeGroupRole() method:


          User sally = identityManager.getUser("sally");
Role admin = identityManager.getRole("administrator");
Group doctors = identityManager.getGroup("doctors");
identityManager.revokeGroupRole(sally, admin, doctors);



          To test whether an identity has a particular group role, you can use the hasGroupRole() method:


          User sally = identityManager.getUser("sally");
Role admin = identityManager.getRole("administrator");
Group doctors = identityManager.getGroup("doctors");
boolean isSallyDoctorsAdmin = identityManager.hasGroupRole(sally, admin, doctors);
